The proper way to install Ubuntu studio for all your creative endeavors, whether it be digital arts or photography or videography or writing or music needs

First you start with Ubuntu live server ISO 

Then you create a beautiful Dis using either UUI or YUMI or bitetcher or any other ISO to live boot USB software

Plug your USB that you just made into the device that you wish to install it in (unless you’re using VMware fusion or VMware workstation or virtual box in which case you do not need the USB you only need the ISO) 

Then boot up your machine, whether it is a physical machine or a virtual machine and have a targeted boot that either reads that USB if it’s a physical device or reads that ISO if it’s a virtual machine first 

Go through the installation process of the live boot 

When prompted install  MaaS as well as NextCloud 

Then finish the installation and restart your machine, Weather physical or virtual with a targeted boot targeting the boot drive 

———- 

Login to Ubuntu server typing your admin credentials or your login credentials if just a user

When at the command line type the following 

- Become admin I.e. super user must enter password to become super user

& sudo su
Input password

- Update and upgrade Package List:

$ Apt  update -y && apt upgrade -y

- Install Ubuntu studio installer file

$ apt install ubuntustudio-installer

- Install Ubuntu studio optimization packages

$ ubuntustudio-installer

- Install genome software center GUI

$ apt install gnome-software

- Install cinnamon desktop GUI

$ apt install cinnamon-desktop-environment

- Install cinnamon desktop optimized for Ubuntu

$ apt install ubuntucinnamon-desktop

- Install audio packages

$ apt install ubuntustudio-audio

- Install graphics packages

$ apt install ubuntustudio-graphics

- Install video packages

$ sudo apt install ubuntustudio-video

- install low latency audio

$ apt install linux-lowlatency


- Install Synaptic: Use the apt installcommand to install Synaptic package manager GUI

$ synaptic

- Install MaaS (Metal as a Servise) stable VM using snap 

$ snap install maas --channel=latest/stable

- Install MaaS (Metal as a Service) repositories 

$ apt-add-repository ppa:maas/stable

Update Package List:

$ Apt  update -y && apt upgrade -y

Install MAAS (Metal as a Service): 
MAAS is typically installed via snap packages

$ apt install maas

Using snap(Recommended)

$ apt install maas-cli

Using the MAAS PPA and apt

$ maas apikey --username=$PROFILE > $API_KEY_FILE 

Obtain the API Key: 
You need an API key to authenticate with the MAAS API. If you have an administrator account, you can get its API key from the region controller

$ maas login $PROFILE $MAAS_URL - < $API_KEY_FILE

Log in to the MAAS CLI: 
Once you have the API key, log in to the MAAS CLI:

$ maas $PROFILE --help

Interact with MAAS: 
After logging in, you can use the maas command followed by your profile name and the desired subcommand to interact with MAAS. For example: View help.

$ maas $PROFILE machines read

commission a machine

$ maas $PROFILE machine commission $SYSTEM_ID

Replace $SYSTEM_ID with the ID of the machine you want to commission. Deploy a machine

$ maas $PROFILE machine deploy $SYSTEM_ID

 Example Workflow (Setting DNS and Importing Images):

$ # Set the upstream DNS server
maas $PROFILE maas set-config name=upstream_dns value="8.8.8.8"

$ # Import images (e.g., Ubuntu 22.04 LTS)
maas $PROFILE boot-resources import

- Restart your machine

$ sudo reboot

- You should see a GUY however, if you do not in order to get to cinnamon desktop you simply input

$ startx 

- If that does not work, you may need to install init

$ sudo apt install init
Password

- Then to start the GUI you simply input

$ init

Or

$ startx 

