Troubleshooting

This command will typically read your ~/.xinitrc file. To ensure Cinnamon starts, you should have the following line in your ~/.xinitrc file

$ exec cinnamon-session

If you need the software rendering version of Cinnamon (often used for troubleshooting or on systems without proper graphics drivers), you would use:

$ exec cinnamon-session-cinnamon2d

From another Desktop Environment or a Terminal within an X Session: 
If you are already in another graphical environment and want to switch to Cinnamon, or if you want to restart Cinnamon, you can use the following commands in a terminal:
* To restart Cinnamon without losing open applications (similar to Alt+F2, then 'r'):

$ pkill -HUP -f "cinnamon --replace"

Or

$ killall -HUP cinnamon

* To explicitly start a new Cinnamon session (if one isn't running or you want a fresh start):
Code

$  cinnamon --replace & disown

Or

$ nohup cinnamon --replace &

